<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=288&amp;p=1939#p1939"><![CDATA[
A simple memory map would fit nicely in the first few lessons.  Something along the lines of:<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">CPU space &#40;directly accessible&#41;:<br />$0000 - $07FF  2KiB  Built-in RAM &#40;freely read/write&#41;<br />$2000 - $2007        Video registers &#40;special functions&#41;<br />$4000 - $401F        Sound and Gamepad registers &#40;special functions&#41;<br />$6000 - $7FFF  8KiB  Optional on-cartridge RAM &#40;freely read/write&#41;<br />$8000 - $FFFF 32KiB  Program ROM &#91;PRG-ROM&#93; &#40;read-only&#41;<br /><br />PPU space &#40;accessible through $2006 and $2007&#41;:<br />$0000 - $1FFF  8KiB  Pattern tables &#40;ROM or RAM, depending on cartridge type&#41;<br />$2000 - $27FF  2KiB  Name and Attribute tables &#40;internal RAM&#41;<br />$3F00 - $3F1F        Palettes &#40;internal RAM&#41;<br /><br />Sprite space &#40;accessible through $2003, $2004, and $4014&#41;:<br />$00 - $FF  256B  Sprite data<br /></div><br />along with an explanation that all code is stored in the PRG-ROM, variables and RAM tables have to be manually initialized, Name tables need to be set up, and so on.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=13">abonetochew</a> — Mon Apr 25, 2005 6:46 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
